# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: microui
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:microui/bitmap] In computing, a **bitmap** (also called **raster**) graphic is an image formed from rows of different colored pixels.
[src:microui/bitmap] A GIF is an example of a graphics image file that uses a bitmap.
[src:microui/bitmap] As a noun, the term "bitmap" is very often used to refer to a particular bitmapping application: the **pix-map**, which refers to a map of pixels, where each pixel may store more than two colors, thus using more than one bit per pixel.
[src:microui/bitmap] In such a case, the domain in question is the array of pixels which constitute a digital graphic output device (a screen or monitor).
[src:microui/bitmap] In some contexts, the term *bitmap* implies one bit per pixel, whereas *pixmap* is used for images with multiple bits per pixel.
[src:microui/bitmap] A bitmap is a type of memory organization or image file format used to store digital images.
[src:microui/bitmap] The term *bitmap* comes from the computer programming terminology, meaning just a *map of bits*, a spatially mapped array of bits.
[src:microui/bitmap] Now, along with *pixmap*, it commonly refers to the similar concept of a spatially mapped array of pixels.
[src:microui/bitmap] Raster images in general may be referred to as bitmaps or pixmaps, whether synthetic or photographic, in files or memory.
[src:microui/bitmap] Many graphical user interfaces use bitmaps in their built-in graphics subsystems.
[src:microui/bitmap] For example, the Microsoft Windows and OS/2 platforms' GDI subsystem uses the *Windows and OS/2 bitmap file format*, usually named with the file extension `.BMP` (or `.DIB` for *device-independent bitmap*).
[src:microui/bitmap] Besides BMP, other file formats that store literal bitmaps include InterLeaved Bitmap (ILBM), Portable Bitmap (PBM), X Bitmap (XBM), and Wireless Application Protocol Bitmap (WBMP).
[src:microui/bitmap] Similarly, most other image file formats, such as JPEG, TIFF, PNG, and GIF, also store bitmap images (as opposed to vector graphics), but they are not usually referred to as *bitmaps*, since they use compressed formats internally.
[src:microui/bitmap] In typical uncompressed bitmaps, image pixels are generally stored with a variable number of bits per pixel which identify its color (the color depth).
[src:microui/bitmap] Pixels of 8 bits and fewer can represent either grayscale or indexed color.
[src:microui/bitmap] An alpha channel (for transparency) may be stored in a separate bitmap, where it is similar to a grayscale bitmap, or in a fourth channel that, for example, converts 24-bit images to 32 bits per pixel.
[src:microui/bitmap] The bits representing the bitmap pixels may be packed or unpacked (spaced out to byte or word boundaries), depending on the format or device requirements.
[src:microui/bitmap] Depending on the color depth, a pixel in the picture will occupy at least *n*/8 bytes, where *n* is the bit depth.
[src:microui/bitmap] where width and height are given in pixels.
[src:microui/bitmap] In the formula above, header size and color palette size, if any, are not included.
[src:microui/bitmap] Due to effects of row padding to align each row start to a storage unit boundary, such as a word, additional bytes may be needed.
[src:microui/bitmap] Microsoft has defined a particular representation of color bitmaps of different color depths, as an aid to exchanging bitmaps between devices and applications with a variety of internal representations.
[src:microui/bitmap] They called these device-independent bitmaps "DIBs", and the file format for them is called DIB file format or BMP file format.
[src:microui/bitmap] Here, "device independent" refers to the format, or storage arrangement, and should not be confused with device-independent color.
[src:microui/bitmap] The X Window System uses a similar XBM format for black-and-white images, and XPM (*pixelmap*) for color images.
[src:microui/bitmap] Numerous other uncompressed bitmap file formats are in use, though most not widely.
[src:microui/bitmap] For most purposes, standardized compressed bitmap files such as GIF, PNG, TIFF, and JPEG are used.
[src:microui/bitmap] Lossless compression in particular provides the same information as a bitmap in a smaller file size.
[src:microui/bitmap] TIFF is usually either uncompressed, or lossless Lempel–Ziv–Welch compressed like GIF.
[src:microui/bitmap] PNG uses deflate lossless compression, another Lempel-Ziv variant.
[src:microui/bitmap] There are also a variety of "raw" image files, which store raw bitmaps with no other information.
[src:microui/bitmap] Such raw files are just bitmaps in files, often with no header or size information (they are distinct from photographic raw image formats, which store raw unprocessed sensor data in a structured container such as TIFF format along with extensive image metadata).
[src:microui/graphical-widget] In a graphical user interface (GUI), a **graphical widget** (also **graphical control element** or **control**) is an element of interaction, such as a button or a scroll bar.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] Controls are software components that a computer user interacts with through direct manipulation to read or edit information about an application.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] User interface libraries such as Windows Presentation Foundation, Qt, GTK, and Cocoa, contain a collection of controls and the logic to render these.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] Each widget facilitates a specific type of user-computer interaction, and appears as a visible part of the application's GUI as defined by the theme and rendered by the rendering engine.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] The theme makes all widgets adhere to a unified aesthetic design and creates a sense of overall cohesion.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] Some widgets support interaction with the user, for example labels, buttons, and check boxes.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] Others act as containers that group the widgets added to them, for example windows, panels, and tabs.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] Structuring a user interface with widget toolkits allows developers to reuse code for similar tasks, and provides users with a common language for interaction, maintaining consistency throughout the whole information system.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] Graphical user interface builders facilitate the authoring of GUIs in a WYSIWYG manner employing a user interface markup language.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] They automatically generate all the source code for a widget from general descriptions provided by the developer, usually through direct manipulation.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] Around 1920, *widget* entered American English, as a generic term for any useful device, particularly a product manufactured for sale; a gadget.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] In 1988, the term *widget* is attested in the context of Project Athena and the X Window System.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] The same year, in the manual *X Toolkit Widgets - C Language X Interface* by Ralph R.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] Finally, still in the same year, Ralph R.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] Any widget displays an information arrangement changeable by the user, such as a window or a text box.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] The defining characteristic of a widget is to provide a single interaction point for the direct manipulation of a given kind of data.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] In other words, widgets are basic visual building blocks which, combined in an application, hold all the data processed by the application and the available interactions on this data.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] GUI widgets are graphical elements used to build the human-machine-interface of a program.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] GUI widgets are implemented like software components.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] Widget toolkits and software frameworks, like e.g.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] GTK+ or Qt, contain them in software libraries so that programmers can use them to build GUIs for their programs.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] A family of common reusable widgets has evolved for holding general information based on the Palo Alto Research Center Inc. research for the Xerox Alto User Interface.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] Various implementations of these generic widgets are often packaged together in widget toolkits, which programmers use to build graphical user interfaces (GUIs).
[src:microui/graphical-widget] Most operating systems include a set of ready-to-tailor widgets that a programmer can incorporate in an application, specifying how it is to behave.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] Each type of widget generally is defined as a class by object-oriented programming (OOP).
[src:microui/graphical-widget] Therefore, many widgets are derived from class inheritance.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] In the context of an application, a widget may be *enabled* or *disabled* at a given point in time.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] An enabled widget has the capacity to respond to events, such as keystrokes or mouse actions.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] A widget that cannot respond to such events is considered disabled.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] The appearance of a widget typically differs depending on whether it is enabled or disabled; when disabled, a widget may be drawn in a lighter color ("**grayed out**") or be obscured visually in some way.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] On pop-up dialogues, buttons might appear greyed out shortly after appearance to prevent accidental clicking or inadvertent double-tapping.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] Widgets are sometimes qualified as *virtual* to distinguish them from their physical counterparts, e.g.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] *virtual* buttons that can be clicked with a pointer, vs. physical buttons that can be pressed with a finger (such as those on a computer mouse).
[src:microui/graphical-widget] A related (but different) concept is the desktop widget, a small specialized GUI application that provides some visual information and/or easy access to frequently used functions such as clocks, calendars, news aggregators, calculators and desktop notes.
[src:microui/graphical-widget] These kinds of widgets are hosted by a widget engine.
[src:microui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] without the use of extensive indirection – thus***immediate***– to retained resources.
[src:microui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] It does not preclude the use of double-buffering.
[src:microui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] Retained mode is an alternative approach.
[src:microui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] Historically, retained mode has been the dominant style in GUI libraries; however, both can coexist in the same library and are not necessarily exclusive in practice.
[src:microui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] In immediate mode, the scene (complete object model of the rendering primitives) is retained in the memory space of the client, instead of the graphics library.
[src:microui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] This implies that in an immediate mode application, the lists of graphical objects to be rendered are kept by the client and are not saved by the graphics library API.
[src:microui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] The application must re-issue all drawing commands required to describe the entire scene each time a new frame is required, regardless of actual changes.
[src:microui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] This method provides on the one hand a maximum of control and flexibility to the application program, but on the other hand it also generates continuous work load on the CPU.
[src:microui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] Examples of immediate mode rendering systems include Direct2D, OpenGL and Quartz.
[src:microui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] There are some immediate mode GUIs that are particularly suitable when used in conjunction with immediate mode rendering systems.
[src:microui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] Primitive vertex attribute data may be inserted frame by frame into a command buffer by a rendering API.
[src:microui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] This involves significant bandwidth and processor time (especially if the graphics processing unit is on a separate bus), but may be advantageous for data generated dynamically by the CPU.
[src:microui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] It is less common since the advent of increasingly versatile shaders, with which a graphics processing unit may generate increasingly complex effects without the need for CPU intervention.
[src:microui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] Graphical user interfaces traditionally use retained mode-style API design, but immediate mode GUIs instead use an immediate mode-style API design, in which user code directly specifies the GUI elements to draw in the user input loop.
[src:microui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] For example, rather than having a CreateButton() function that a user would call once to instantiate a button, an immediate-mode GUI API may have a DoButton() function which should be called whenever the button should be on screen.
[src:microui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] The technique was developed by Casey Muratori in 2002.
[src:microui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] Prominent implementations include Omar Cornut's Dear ImGui in C++, Nic Barker's Clay in C and Micha Mettke's Nuklear in C.
[src:microui/layout-computing] In computing, **layout** is the process of calculating the position of objects in space subject to various constraints.
[src:microui/layout-computing] This functionality can be part of an application or packaged as a reusable component or library.
[src:microui/retained-mode] Immediate mode is an alternative approach.
[src:microui/retained-mode] Historically, retained mode has been the dominant style in GUI libraries; however, both can coexist in the same library and are not necessarily exclusionary in practice.
[src:microui/retained-mode] In retained mode the client calls do not directly cause actual rendering, but instead update an abstract internal model (typically a list of objects) which is maintained within the library's data space.
[src:microui/retained-mode] This allows the library to optimize when actual rendering takes place along with the processing of related objects.
[src:microui/retained-mode] Example of coexistence with immediate mode in the same library is OpenGL.
[src:microui/retained-mode] OpenGL has immediate mode functions that can use previously defined server side objects (textures, vertex buffers and index buffers, shaders, etc.) without resending unchanged data.
[src:microui/retained-mode] Examples of retained mode rendering systems include Windows Presentation Foundation, SceneKit on macOS, and PHIGS.
